{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868880/1930061401/0056.xml":{"full_text":"Page T*\u00ab!u\u00bb\nIt bam to Me\nwwr\nKVWOOD BROUN\nTIME, so it seems, hangs heavily upon the hands of\nsocial leaders. At any rate, Mrs. Ruth G. K. Straw\nbridge has taken to writing letters again. Mrs. Straw\nbridge you may remember as the lady from Philadelphia\nwho went to Washington some months ago to inform a\nsenate committee that prohibition could be solved if only\npersons in the social register would refrain from serving\ncocktails.\nThe announcement of this novel idea put Mrs. Strawbridge on the*\nfront page of practically all the newspapers. After resting on her\nlaurels for a little while she has decided to venture forth again, and\nin her quiet and genteel way she has begun sending several thousand\nletters to the better people here in New York.\nHer communication, I am informed, reads in part as follows:\nMrs. Strawbridge Takes Pen in Hand.\nY DEJAR MRS.\nIVJI \u201ci am taking the liberty of addressing myself to you as a\nrepresentative New York woman to inquire quite confidentially whether\nin your judgment it would be possible to constitute a committee of\nwomen of your own standing in the social world who would interest\nthemselves in creating sentiment for the observance of the prohibition\n\nlaw within their own circles.\n\u201cThere has, no doubt, recently come to your attention the notable\nexample set by Mrs. Edward B. McLean of Washington in this re\nspect. I am sending you herewith a photostat copy of the newspaper\narticle which was published about Mrs. McLean\u2019s Easter breakfast\nparty.\n\u201cI have every reason to believe that her courage in making this\ninnovation in Washington society met with the hearty approval of\nPresident Hoover and of others like himself who are trying to inculcate\nin our people at this time a more lively sense of their individual obli\ngations as American citizens My thought is simply that if people\nwhose wealth and position clothe them with the power of example can\nbe induced to set an example, as Mrs. McLean is trying to do, we could\nbe of inestimable aid to the president In carrying out his program for\nlaw observance and law enforcement by the people themselves.\n\u201cP. s __i sent this letter to 2,000 important families in Philadel\nphia.\u201d\nA Plebeian Is Perplexed.\nI WONDER what it feels like to be a member of the 1,999 th most\nimportant family in Philadelphia.\nTo us commoners the actions of the quality folk in the big white\nhouse quite frequently seem amazing. A search through the entire\nBook of Etiquette fails to furnish me with any precedent for the sin\ngular behavior of Mrs. Strawbridge. In great detail the problem of\nwhether she should ask him in is discussed and also the station a young\nman should assume when walking with two young ladies on a crowded\nthoroughfare. But there is nothing which.fixes a method for meddling\nin the affairs of one's neighbors.\nAlthough *he working day of Mrs. Ruth G. K. Strawbridge does\nnot seem to have been filled to overflowing, she still lacked leisure to\nacquaint herself with the provisions of the prohibition law before she\nwrote her letter. A kindly supreme court has but recently decided that\nno guilt attaches to the buyer. And even before that comfortable doc\nl ine was compounded the fact remained that one might in all good\n\u25a0ouscience serve in his own home such liquor as had been acquired\nbefore the days of Mr. Volstead.\nThat noi hootlegged potion ever graced a Philadelphia table I would\nnot be disposed to argue. As a member of the middle class it is not\nmy custom'to ask any host or hostess, \u201cJust where did you get this\nliquor and is it come by honestly?\u201d Beyond the borders of my home I\ntake, without question, the cocktails and the soup which are set before\nme. I had supposed, in my ignorance of the ways of the socially elect,\nthat this was as fundamental as the injunction not to point, which my\nparents and guardians dinned into me at 4. And so it seems to me that\nthe most impressive thing in the Ruth G. K. Strawbridge inquiry lay\nin the opening phrase, \u201cI am taking the liberty.\u201d\nAs a student of human psychology I should be most interested in\nseeing all the replies in full. I am puzzled by the emphasis put upon\nMrs. McLean\u2019s \u201cEaster breakfast,\u201d where, according to the newspaper\naccounts, only orange juice and ice water were served. To us com\nmoners \u2014even the wet ones \u2014there is nothing particularly extraordinary\nin getting through breakfast without cocktails, whisky sours, rum\npunches or lager beej\\ And, anyhow, orange juice is half the battle.\nIt was, at least, a setup breakfast.\nMrs. Strawbridge, naturally, cannot tell of the replies which she\nlias received. All the many thousand letters which she sent out to the\nmany thousand important families were confidential. But one confi\ndence begets another. I wonder if in the collection there may have\nbeen some single reply reading about as follows:\nJust a Fantasy.\nEAR RUTHIE: Thanks for reminding me about the law and\nof the duties of us social leaders. It is so kind of you to think\nof John (Poodles) J. and myself as important. I did see the news\npaper account of the boozeless breakfast. At least, my secretary called\nmy attention to the article and the pictures buried away there on the\nfront page. I hope you agree with me that it was a vulgar display of\ni passion for publicity.\n\u201cAn older woman like yourself can probably remember back to a\nday when we \u2018important people\u2019 did not think it necessary to call up\nall the local city editors at such times as we decided not to take a\ndrink. There was a day when even social leaders regarded that and\nsimilar subjects as strictly their own business.\n\u201cIncidentally, my dear, I want to make a suggestion to you, and 1\n(rust you will receive it in the same spirit in which I received yours.\nWhere, in heaven s name do you get your scrapple? I was talking it\n\u25a0ver with one of the Biddles only last week, and we both agreed tljat\nsomebody ought to have the courage to tell you about it.\n\u201cIf you could have seen the face of that poor French count who\nattended your delightful banquet last Saturday! He was\\as brave as\nLafayette at Gettysburg or wherever it was that somebody\\said, \u2018Nous\nvoila.\u2019 Don t you find history boring?\n\u201cOf course, maybe it isn\u2019t the scrapple itself. It could be your\nook. Several of us have been meaning to speak to you about her. 1\nwas discussing it with the Drexels last night. So sorry not to find you\ninvited there for the party. But to make a long story longer, I\u2019ll meet\nyou half way on this proposition. If I agree to give up whisky sours\nat my house will you agree to quit serving scrapple at yours? I hope\ni lie children aie well. John sends his love. No wooden nickels, mind\nyou!\u201d'\nThe residence of Mrs. Strawbridge is called Windmere.\nNEWSBOYS PROTEST DRUGGISTS'\nDRIVE FOR NEWS STAND MONOPOLY\nProtesting the resolution of the\n.Milwaukee Pharmaceutical Assn.,\nwhich proposes to ask the common\ncouncil to forbid newsboys to main\ntain stands on downtown corners,\ndeclaring that the boys are unfair\ncompetitors in the druggists\u2019 news\npaper and magazine trade. Ben\njamin Bordow, president, Milwau\nkee Newsboys\u2019 union, No. 334, has\naddressed an open letter to the pub\nlic.\nExcerpts follow:\nDruggists Run General Stores.\u201d\n\u201cI should like to ask the drug\ngists\u2019 association how they figure\nthese stands are unfair competitors\nto them.\nb/^\n\u201cWere not the newsboys on the\ncorners long before drug stores\never attempted to sell magazines?\nDid they not start to sell the news\nboys\u2019 commodity long after the\nnewsboy started in the business?\nDid the newsboys make a complaint\nwhen the drug stores began to com\npete with them as a selling agent?\n1 ask the public: Who is it who\nhas the greatest right to talk un\nfair competition, the druggist or\nthe newsboy?\n\u201cThe public no doubt has noticed\nthat the druggist, who formerly\nwas a vender of herbs and medi\ncines. now has a general store and\nis a competitor of many merchants\nwho make a living on only one line\nMilwaukee Road Plans Addition to Grain Bin\nHeld to Answer\nMurder Charge\ny^\nft hl^\nIS JW\nfc **s^ <Jg\ni 41\nI\nBy Leader Staff Photographer.\nDonald Allison, 38 years (M,\nChicago, had his case continued\nto June 27 today when he was\narraigned in district court\ncharged with the murder of Ur\nsula Lang, 19 years old, who was\nfound dead in the Schroeder ho\ntel Sunday.\nLAWYERS CLASH,\nHURL CHARGES\nIN INJURY CASE\nSerious charges were made by\ntwo attorneys against each other be\nfore Circuit Judge Otto H. Breiden\nbach today in the personal injury\ncase of Andrew Shoknecht against\nArnold Fortman.\nJudge Breidenbaeh ordered At\ntorney Charles Mullen, appearing\nfor Fortman, to divulge information\nregarding the identity of an un\nknown automobile driver who fig\nured in the collision before Monday,\nor be hefd in contempt of court.\nWould Not Divulge Name.\nIn an adverse examination, ac\ncording to Attorney J. Elmer Lehr,\nwho represents the plaintiff, Fort\nman, who has no permanent resi\ndence in Milwaukee, did not give\nthe name of the unknown driver be\ncause he said he had given a mem\norandum concerning it to his attor\nney, Mullen.\nLehr was charged with discour\ntesy by Mullen, who insisted that\nLehr had not inquired as to wheth\ner Mullen was retained in the case\nor had. been paid by the plaintiff.\nWas Retained First.\nMullen, in court, said that he had\nbeen originally retained by the\nplaintiff, Shoknecht, and has not\nbeen paid sls which Shoknecht\nowes him. Shoknecht was a pas\nsenger in Fortman\u2019s automobile\nwhen it collided with the car of the\nunknown driver.\n\u2018My client told me that he had\nnever hired Mullen to act for him,\u201d\ndeclared Lehr, \u201calthough Mullen\nasked him for the case.\u201d\nGood Will Tourists\nBack in Milwaukee\nThe 100 Milwaukee business men\nwho formed the Association of Com\nmerce Good Will tour of Wisconsin\nand upper Michigan returned to\nMilwaukee last night. During the\nfive-day tour, Milwaukee\u2019s good\nwill message was given to 31 vil\nlages, towns and cities.\nHOLD SERVICES\nFOR MRS. FRANTZ,\n82, ON TUESDAY\nLast rites for Mrs. Margaretha\nFrantz, 82 years old, widow of\nCharles Frantz, pioneer undertaker\nof the south side, who died last\nnight at her home, 7G9 Mineral st.,\nwill be conducted at 2 p. m. Tues\nday in the parlors of the Frantz\nfuneral home, 831 Greenfield ave.,\nand at 2:30 p. m. at St. Stephan\u2019s\nchurch, Grove and Scott sts.\nBurial will be in Pilgrims\u2019 Rest\ncemetery.\nMrs. Frantz, who was born in\nNuremberg, Bavaria, came to Mil\nwaukee as a child. She had lived\non the south side for 75 years and\nwas one of the founders of St.\nStephan\u2019s church.\nFive children, Paul, George, Mrs.\nFred Mootz, Mrs. Alvina Mootz and\nMrs. Meta Zentgraf and seven\ngrandchildren and one great grand\nchild survive her.\nof merchandise.\n\u201cAnd now these druggists want\nto take the livelihood from the poor\nnewsboy by taking away his news\nstand. I feel the public is with the\nnewsboy, and I am sure the com\nmon council of Milwaukee realizes\nthat all prosperous cities must\nhave news stands. Had the drug\ngist complained that corner boys\nwere a nuisance ll and detriment to\ntheir business, there might be rea\nson for complaint.\n\u201cLive and Let Live.\u201d\n\u201cTo condemn the news stands,\nhowever, is beyond our sense of\njudgment. The newsboys have\nformed an association for their\nprotection. We believe in live and\nlet live. Our existence depends on\nthe sale of newspapers and maga\nzines. We cannot sell anything\nelse, as the druggist can.\u201d\nThe druggists\u2019 petition was filed\nyesterday for presentation to the\ncommon council Monday,\nTHE MILWAUKEE LEADER. SATURDAY. TUNE 14, 1930\nHOLDS SCHOOL\nCONSOLIDATION\nUP VIS WRITS\nTemporary injunctions \"were grant\ned today by Circuit Judge Otto H.\nBreidenbaeh against Officers of\nschool district No. 8, town of Green\nfield, to prevent them from proceed\ning with the consolidation of school\ndistrict No. 8 with school district\nNo. 14, which is partly in the town\nof Lake and partly in the town of\nGreenfield.\nPoint Out Effect.\nThe effect of the consolidation of\nthe two school districts, it was ar\ngued, would place control in the\nsouthern district known as No. 14.\nThe present school site, it was\npointed out, would be outside of the\nterritory of the two districts' and\nCharles Goedicke, one of the direc\ntors of district No. 8, would be au\ntomatically ousted from office be\ncause he would not be a resident of\nthe new territory.\nThree Are Defendants.\nThe defendants in the case are\nFred Wiese, John Mitchell and\nAnna Netz, officers of district No. 8.\nPARENT-TEACHER\nBODIES URGED\nTO MAKE BUDGET\nBecause control of aU depart\nments of the Milwaukee school\nboard is made through budgets,\nparent-teacherif associations were\nadvised to work on the 1932 school\nprogram at a meeting of the Par\nent-Teachers\u2019 Assn, council at the\nWisconsin hotel last night.\nThe Neeskara School Assn., re\nported through R. L. Stapleton,\nthat the budget for 1931 was al\nready made and improvements not\nlisted should be noted for 1932.\nCommittee chairmen, to consti\ntute the board of managers of the\ncouncil, were announced as follows:\nMrs. Clara Ray, Mrs. George Zach\now, Mrs. Charles McGinnis, Miss\nClara Manthe, Mrs. B. J. Dunlop..\nMrs. John Yoss, Mrs. Ray Haissler.\nMrs. W. S. Churches, Mrs. George\nKemnitz, Mrs. F. J. Klinka, Mrs.\nLeon Glasgow, Mrs. Austin Town\nsend, Mrs. Frank Schwinn, Mrs.\nJames Barr, H. H. Smith and M.\nA. Streratb.\nButcher Sues for\n$5,000 Claiming\nFamily Slandered\nReflections on the ancestry of\nMaryon Skitek, 678 Seventeenth\nave., a butcher, are valued at $5,000\nin his suit for slander against\nTheofil \u2018Bogrowski filed in circuit\ncourt today. The complaint alleges\nthat Theofil, Sept. 11 last, in the\npresence of several persons, made\nderogatory remarks in Polish\nabout Maryon.\nHead of Shorewood\nHigh School Quits\nOscar Granger, principal of\nShorewood High school, notified\nthe villige board of education yes\nterday that he had accepted the\nprincipalship of Haverford Town\nship High school, near Philadel\nphia, and submitted his resignation.\nVeteran of Relief\nDrives to Organize\nA Milwaukee county branch of\nthe Veterans of the Philippine and\nChina relief campaigns will be or\nganized at 8 tonight in the National\nSoldiers\u2019 home recreation hall. Pen\nsion and other legislation affecting\nsuch veterans will be outlined by\nspeakers.\nFISK RUBBER CO.\nTO HALVE FORCE\nThe force of employes of the Cud\nahy plant of the Fisk Rubber Co.\nvill be cut down about half between\nnow anti July 1, according to B. H.\nPratt, vice president, who returned\nyesterday from a conference with\nofficials of the parent company.\nThe force numbers about i,300.\nNormally about 10,000 tires a day\nare supplied to automobile manu\nfacturers, but the plant has pro\nduced tires faster than they could\nbe absorbed by the industry, Pratt\nexplained.\n\u201cWe are merely slowing down to\nwait for the automobile manufac\nturers to catch up, and hope to go\nback to our normal production scale\nwithin a short time,\u201d he said.\nNEWSPAPER MAN\nTO TALK BEFORE\nADVERTISING MEN\nLee A. White of The Detroit\nNews will speak on Style in Adver\ntising before the Milwaukee Adver\ntising club at a dinner meeting at\n6:15 p. m. Wed\nthe University or 1\nWashington, Seat- lee A h,te\ntie and associate professor of jour\nnalism at the University of Michi\ngan.\nj -1- oi-rf;.:.\n4.,.. I O \u00bb\u00abK*v I j\nj \u2014j j\nj m i fe\u201efr7 T \u2018~T r i\n\nMODEL SU&DiyrSIO fl Vi ATi GAS PL tt'aftb FLOWED \u2018SHOW\n\u25a0\u25a0nawaags^.^.;vm r^\u00bbvff:v^rtlir-Vy-V\nThree prizes are offered for the\nbest names for a new type of sub\ndivision designed by the Boer\nner Co., landscape architects for\nthe State Garden and Flower\nshow in the Auditorium, June 20\nto 22. The plan shown above\nshows only the central unit of the\nRITES FOR 103-\nYEAR-OLD MAN\nWILL BE HELD\nThe body of Alexander Bushey,\n103 years old, who died today at\nthe home of his daughter, Mrs.\nJames Stewart, 788 National ave.,\nwill be taken tonight to Bayfield,\nWis., his former home, for funeral\nservices and burial.\nFuneral arrangements will not be\nmade until after the arrival of the\nfuneral party in Bayfield.\nA pioneer lumberman and sailor,\nMr. Bushey was born in Bathurst,\nN. 8., during the lumber boom in\nthat region.\nLived Here Nine Years.\nForty-five years ago he followed\nthe trail of woodsmen from Canada\ninto Wisconsin and settled at Bay\nfield, where he lived until nine\nyears ago, coming to Milwaukee at\nthat time to live with his daughter.\nHe retired from business 14 years\nago.\nAte Vegetables, Fish.\nHis longevity was ascribed by\nMr. Bushey to a diet of vegetables\nand fish, hard work and a clean\nmind.\nAmong the survivors are two\nsons, Charles, Chicago; William,\nSpooner, Wis., and three daughters,\nMrs/ Stewart, Mrs. Joe Vinnett,\nHammond, Ind., and Mrs. Elizabeth\nCabe, Edyfield.\nBurglars Get $65\nIn State St. Store\nBursters, believed to be boys, en\ntered the Oscar Stoltz drug store at\n1380 State st. early today and took\n$65 worth of fountain pens and\nsome small change from a cash reg\nister. The thieves entered by smash\ning the glass in a door.\nSlow Progress of Some\nIn $20,000 Prize Contest\nIs Aiding Tardy Entrants\nFrom present indications some of\nthe big cars included in the $20,-\n000 prize list provided in The Mil\nwaukee Leader\u2019s Gift Distribution\nare going to be given away for less\nvotes than usually are required\nwhen a \u201cLizzie,\u201d a sewing machine,\na phonograph, a radio set, a wrist\nwatch or a diamond ring are given\naway.\nThere are five districts and five\nsets of prizes, each topped by a big\nbeautiful sedan. Think of it \u2014eight\nbig beautiful automobiles in all.\nThe first prize in each district is a\nsedan. The $20,000 gift list in\ncludes cars and cash. The cars, all\npurchased in Milwaukee, are of\nknown value and worth and the\ncash prizes are good old coin of the\nrealm. You don\u2019t have to guess as\nto the value of these prizes. More\nthan this, every active candidate is\nguaranteed a cash payment of 10\nper cent of his or her subscription\ncollections if he or she fails to win\na prize.\nPep Is Advantage.\nThere are more candidates listed\nwho have not accomplished any\nthing than there are those who\nhave. The campaign is not really\nunder way. Certainly some candi\ndates have not hit their stride yet.\nAnd white candidates \u201cdilly-daily\u201d\nalong there are thousands in Mil\nwan!, je and the territory round\nabout who are simply waiting to\nlie asked to subscribe.\nLive, earnest, energetic candi\ndates \u2014subscription getters\u2014can en\nter today and walk away from the\nslow-going entries. Any one now\nentered can put pep. speed and ac\ntion into his campaign and accom\nplish real things. There is no han\ndier for you in this campaign ex\nti e h~~\" -n make for\n\u2022self by lack of effort.\nVotes turned in so far would not\njustify one of the old-time piano,\nsewing machine and ring cam-\npaigns. That is the honest truth. All candidates are asked to re-\nThe lade of interest in their cam- pert wirh a club or more of sub\nten fortunes manifested by can- \u201cion Saturday, June 14. Will\ndictates in general is more than re- ou have a club?\n3 PRIZES OFFERED FOR NAMES\nproposed development. The homes\nwill be on lots 60 by 120 feet,\nfacing open landscaped areas 90\nfeet wide. All this is grouped\naround a school and playground.\nLots in the adjoining blocks have\naccess to the school without street\ncrossings and lots in blocks north\nand south of through streets will\nPLAN EXHIBITS OF ALL KINDS\nAT STATE GARDEN FLOWER SHOW\nNot only ent flowers, consisting\nof peonies, perennials and roses,\nbut gardens built by nursrymen and\ngarden clubs, and exhibits of lunch\neon tables, shadow boxes, room dec\noration, miniature models and mini\nature home grounds will be shown\nat the State Garden and Flower\nshow at the Auditorium June 20\nand 22.\nCommittees in charge of projects\nand exhibits are as follows:\nShadow boxes: Class A, Mrs. A.\nNoerenberg; class B, Mrs. Edward\nCorrigan; class C. Mrs. E. C.\nIlaasch.\nLuncheon tables: Class A, Sunday\nevening supper tables, Mrs. Henry\nHobberg; class B, special occasion\ntables, Mrs. Owen Pritchard; class\nC, formal dinner tables, Mrs. John\nPaul, Sr.\nExhibition gardens, Mrs. Chester\nThomas.\nMiniature models, Mrs. John Le-\nFeber.\nRoom decoration, Mrs. Robert\nStoll and Mrs A. W. Krieger.\nPosters, Dr. H. Nolte.\nSpecial exhibits, Miss Celia Dix,\nMrs. Theodore Koerner.\nCut Flowers Exhibits.\nThe committees for the cut flow\ners are:\nPeonies, Mrs. George Leverenz.\nMiss Mabel Thoms, Mr. L. Potter,\nMrs. August Peters, Mrs. Lisle Mor\nton.\nPerennials, Mrs. Klingbeil, Mrs.\nM. Vander Hogt, Mrs. C. Pohlman\nand Mrs. S. Wedgewood.\nRoses, Mrs. William Hopkinson\nand August Peters.\nIris, Mrs. O. J. Reuss and A.\nJaeger,\nList of Committees.\nThe general committees are:\nLay-out and design, Alfred\nBoerner.\nPublicity, Huron Smith and Fay\nCoon.\ngrettable\u2014it is appalling. Really,\nit is ridiculous that prizes like\nthese offered by The Milwaukee\nLeader should be compelled to seek\nthe candidate instead of the candi\ndate going out after them.\nHere The Milwauke Leader is\nputting up over $20,000 in big,\nhandsome, speedy cars \u2014all closed\njobs\u2014and real, honest-to-goodness\ncash prizes. And some entered are\ncontent to stand by and let then\nfriends cast their votes for them.\nHit Your Stride.\nIt is a fact that in some cases\nmore yotes have been cast for a\ncandidate by subscribers paying\ntheir subscriptions over the coun\nter than the r-\u00ab>\u25a0\u25a0'\u00bb late has produced\nhimself. This means that friends\nwho would subscribe come to The\nMilwaukee Leader office and pay\ntheir subscription over the counter\nwithout solicitation and because\nthey want their friends to have the\nbenefit of the votes, cast them for\nr \"\u2019r favorite.\nCandidates should manifest some\nenthusiasm on their own account\nand go out to win, for winning any\none of these eight cars, to say\nnothing of the cash awards, will\nmean as much compensation to the\ncandidate as most regular occupa\ntions pay in an entire year\u2019s time.\nSooner or later a candidate or\ncandidates entered or yet to enter\nwill hit their stride and the <te\"ves\n-\u2022\u2022e going to f od themselves weep\ning in sackcloth and ashes at the\nroadside while the \u201clive wires\u201d\nspeed past in their big motor cars\n\u2014r rds v \u2019\u2019\u2022\u2022nii'di consistent es\nfort. No one needs to be a drone.\nEvery one has it in himself or her\nself to accomplish. And the tteie\naccomplish right now, this big\nfirst period, when the biggest vote\nschedule of the entire 'wnpaign is\neffective. M -->ukee Leader\ninvites you to help T'wrself. Will\nyou?\nList of Exhibits.\nconnect with the school by sub\nway crossings. The prizes will\nbe $lO, $3 and $2. Each contest\nant Is limited, to three names and\nthe names must be submitted in\na sealed envelope to Name Judge,\nState Garden and Flower Show,\nAuditorium, before 5:30 p. m.\nThursday.\nMusic, Mrs. J. Gaines and Mrs.\nJohn LeFeber.\nPatrons and patronesses, Miss L.\nA. Sealman and Mrs. W. A. Bowers.\nBoys\u2019 and girls\u2019 club work, Fay\nCoon.\nGeneral entry committee, Mrs.\nJames Johnson.\nThe general manager is H. J.\nRabmlow, Madison, assisted by E.\nC. Haasch, Wauwatosa.\nKOTECK! ADDS\nFOUR QUERIES\nON BOOK DEAL\nThe controversy over the five-year\ncontract of the Hampel Book Shop,\n218 Wells st., to supply the library\nboard with trade books, was fur\nther complicated late yesterday\nCity Controller Louis M. Kotecki\nadded four inquiries, questioning\nthe validity of the contract, to the\nmany already submitted At\ntorney John M. Niven.\nAt the close of a conference be\ntween the entire official staff of\nthe controller's qfiice, Assistant\nCity Attorney Charles W. Babcock\nand M. S. Dudgeqn, library board\nsecretary, questions into the follow\ning phases of the contract were\nsent to the city attorney:\nAsks About Contract.\nDid the library board have the\nright, under a resolution from the\ncity purchasing board authorizing it\nto do its own buying of goods to be\nused only by it, to enter into a con\ntract itself or should such a con\ntract have been executed by the\npurchasing board and countersigned\nby the controller?\nWould it be legal for uven the\npurchasing board to enter into a\nlive-year contract, the time being\nlonger than the terms of office of\nits members and involving expendi\nture of more funds than they could\nknow at the time would be avail\nable?\n\u201cDuties of Controller?\u201d\nIs the controller permitted to or\ncan he be compelled to countersign\na contract extending over his own\nterm of office?\nIs a contract with the Hampel\nBook Shop legal in view of the fact\nthat George Hampel, its president,\nholds a city office as secretary of\nthe motion picture commission?\nToday Is Flag Day\nFlags on Display;\nSchool Ceremonies\nA display of flags on public\nbuildings and homes throughout the\ncity marked Milwaukee\u2019s observance\nof Flag day today.\nThe 153rd anniversary of the\nadoption of Old Glory was remem\nbered in the city schools yesterday.\nSpecial ceremonies were held at\nSouth Division High school, Lincoln\nHigh school, Peckham, Steuben and\nWalker Junior High schools.\nNo municipal programs were\nplanned.\nINJUNCTION IS\nDENIED WEST CO.\nInjunctions and the appointment\nof a .receiver for the West Lumber\nCo. were denied by Circuit Court\nJudge John J. Gregory today.\nA temporray injunction granted\nseveral days ago by Circuit Judge\nDaniel W. Sullivan also was dis\nsolved.\nThe suit was brought by Rose\nG. Silverberg, holder of common\nstock of the par value of $7,000\nagainst the company and its offi\ncers and directors.\nLosses of $450,000 were sustained\nby the lumber company between\n1920 and 1927, she alleged. In\nspite of these losses, she charges,\nthe officers paid preferred stock\ndividends of $85,000.\nJudge Gregory remarked that no\nshowing was made of any present\ndanger to the capital or assets of\n(he company and that no receiver\nshould therefore be anoointed.\nilg\u00dfSfefc. 3\nNORTH WESTERN\nALSO TO BUILD\nNEW ELEVATOR\nSBOO,OOO to Be Spent\non Both Projects\nHere.\nCo-incident with the issuance of a\npermit to the North Western road\ntoday for the construction of a\n$500,000 grain storage bin on the\nbank of the Kinnickinnic river,\nsouth of Greenfield are., the Mil\nwaukee road today announced that\ncontracts will be awarded next\nweek for erection of a 2,000,000\nbushel capacity addition to the pres\nent elevator on the Menomonee\ncanal.\nThe North Western road's bin\nwill be 9S feet high and will have a\ncapacity of 2,908,917 cubic feet, ac\ncording to Building Inspector Leon\nM. Gurda.\nCost Near $300,000.\nThe announcement of the new\ngrain elevator was made by H. A.\nScandrett, president, of The Mil.\nwaukee road, although details as\nto the exact construction were not\nrevealed.\nThe present elevator has 1,500,000\nbushels capacity. It is expected by\nlocal officials that the addition will\nbe constructed of reinforced con\ncrete in the silo style, to conform\nwith the present elevator. The ad\ndition will cost more than $300,000,\nit is said.\nExpects Business Revival.\n\u201cIt may be considered remark\nable that the road should start to\nwork during the present depres\nsion,\u2019' Scandrett. said, \u201cbut we feel\nthe depression has reached its low\nest ebb, and business will start to\npick up soon.\n\u201cIt should be fair by September\nand should be back to normal by\nDecember, at the latest.\u2019\u2019\nThe present reinforced concrete\nelevator was built after the old\nelevator, for years a landmark\naround Milwaukee, was burned\nabout five years ago.\nStart Using Dial\nPhones at Four\nExchanges Tonight\nAt 12 tonight the electricians m\nfour dial exchanges of the Wiscon\nsin Telephone Co. will throw the\nswitches and telephone users will\nget their own numbers. The ex\nchanges which will use the dial\nsystem are Bluemound, Daly,\nGreenfield and Marquette. More\nthan 41,000 new and changed tele\nphone numbers appear in the new\ndirectory, and dial phone users are\nasked to use the new books for\neach call under the new system.\nGETS TERM FOR\nSLUGGING BOSS\nPhillip Radtkovich, 26 years old,\n337 Thirty-fourth ave., was sen\nlenced to one year in the house of\ncorrection when he was convicted\ntoday in municipal court of assault\nwith intent to do great bodily 'harm.\nOn May 7, Radtkovich, who sust\nhad been discharged from the Mil\nwaukee road shops, struck Charles\nTacke, 3726 Roberts st., a foreman,\non the head with an iron pipe.\nTacke was in serious condition\nfor several weeks as a result of the\nblow.\nNuisance Charge\nCollapses; Town\nChairman Freed\nThe charge against Paul Welbes,\nchairman of the town of Lake, of\nviolating the prohibition laws in his\nKinnickinnic ave. soft drink parlor,\nhas been dismissed.\nDismissal of the nuisance charge\nwas asked in federal court by E. J.\nKoelzer, assistant prosecutor, be\ncause the case was based on the dry\ndepartment\u2019s informer system and\ndid pot hold, it was learned yester\nday.\nW. Frank Cunningham, dry chief,\nsaid that an informer had made\neight purchases in the Welbes sa\nloon, but when the case was called\nthe informer was not available to\ntestify and therefore the govern\nment\u2019s case collapsed.\nSSOO Expended for, 1\nRamp Approved by\nHarbor Commission\nExpenditure of SSOO by C. U.\nSmith, harbor terminal director, to\nreplace the ramp for amphibian\nplanes on the Maitland air field,\nwas approved last night by the Mil\nwaukee harbor commission. The\nramp was torn from Its moorings by\ngates last October.\nTo Reopen Repaired\nNataborium Tuesday\nAfter being closed four weeks for\nrepairs at a cost of $20,000, the\nGreenbush st. natatorium, 628\nGreenbush st., will be reopened\nTuesday,\n$6,500 IS LOST 1\nIN PLANT FIRE\nEstimated damage of $6,500 was\ncaused bv fire today at the Mon\narch Manufacturing Co. plant, 179-\n181 Chicago St. The fire started\nin the basement, according to Dep\nuty Chief Emil Potorsion\nPage Two","height":"28650","width":"21114"}}
